<br>
Harmony of Sound(HoS) is clearly the superior Debuff, for the short duration that it remains on, especially when used in conjunction with the War Drums of the Rathe, but because of the Spell Slot stacking, HoS is overwritten by these Druid Ro debuffs, <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>all consisting of FIRE debuffs, not MAGIC -- Magic debuffing is why HoS is so desired.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Those druid debuffs are:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Hand of Ro<br>
Ro's Smoldering Disjunction<br>
Ro's Fiery Sundering</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
This is extremely detrimental to a raid during the &quot;control&quot; time period that mob(s) are first pulled into camp, unslowed, and the Debuff Process Begins when <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>HoS,Tash,Malos/ini</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->,etc. are needed for slow, cripple, and even mez to land. <br>
<br>
It never fails that some druid instinctively casts a Ro Debuff and removes HoS just moments before a shaman tries to slow a mob, then the shaman gets resisted, summoned, and killed. HoS is then needing to be re-applied, burning an additional 3-15 seconds of additional unslowed pain and hellfury from the mob on the encounter. (Say Goodbye to your Main Tank!)<br>
<br>
In summary,<br>
HoS, Occlusion, and the Druid Ro Line should stack. There is no real 'gameplay reason' why it shouldn't. This is a spell-stacking issue that has been around as long as the Velious Expansion Era when Occlusion of Sound was introduced.<br>
